# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grpc-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] gRPC uses HTTP/2 for transport, Protocol Buffers as the interface description language, and provides features such as authentication, bidirectional streaming and flow control, blocking or nonblocking bindings, and cancellation and timeouts.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] The most common usage scenarios include connecting services in a microservices style architecture, or connecting mobile device clients to backend services.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] gRPC's use of HTTP trailers makes it impossible to implement a gRPC client in a browser, instead requiring a proxy.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] From about 2001, Google created a general-purpose RPC infrastructure called Stubby to connect the large number of microservices running within and across its data centers.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] In March 2015, Google decided to build the next version of Stubby and make it open source.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] gRPC supports the usage of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and token-based authentication.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] Connection to Google services must use TLS.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] There are two types of credentials: channel credentials and call credentials.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] For token-based authorization, gRPC provides Server Interceptor and a Client Interceptor.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] gRPC uses Protocol Buffers to encode data.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] Protocol buffers provide a serialization format and an interface definition language.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] Some of the software tools used for testing gRPC implementations include Postman, ezy, Insomnia, and Step CI.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] Many organizations use gRPC, including Uber, Square, Netflix, IBM, CoreOS, Docker, CockroachDB, Arista Networks, Cisco, Juniper Networks, Spotify, Zalando, Dropbox, and Google as the original developer.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] The open source project u-bmc uses gRPC to replace Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/grpc] On 8 January 2019, Dropbox announced that the next version of "Courier", their RPC framework at the core of their service-oriented architecture (SOA), would be migrated to be based on gRPC, primarily because it aligned well with their existing custom RPC frameworks.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:grpc-cpp-lib/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
